<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEVEN CHARGED WITH SMUGGLING HAITIANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Seven people were charged Friday with smuggling 411 Haitian refugees to 
southern Florida in a case the prosecutor said was about "the exploitation of 
human misery." 
</P>
<P>
 U.S. Atty. Kendall Coffey said six Haitian refugees were believed to have died 
during the voyage in a 65-foot wooden ship, which arrived off Miami on April 
21. 
</P>
<P>
 "This case is about trafficking in human cargo and the exploitation of human 
misery," Coffey said. 
</P>
<P>
 Unlike many other Haitian refugees, the 411 were allowed to be taken to an 
immigration processing center west of Miami. They were not shipped back to 
Haiti because the boat was too crowded, it lacked safety equipment and many of 
the refugees were sick, authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
