<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: I SUE YOU, YOU SETTLE WITH ME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Barney the dinosaur can sing "I Love You" without worrying about the legal 
consequences, now that agreement has been reached in a court dispute over the 
song. 
</P>
<P>
 The deal was accepted this week by Jean Warren of Everett, who claimed rights 
to the lyrics, and Lyons Group of Dallas, which owns the dinosaur 
character.Terms were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
 Warren sued Lyons 18 months ago, claiming she held the rights to Barney's 
unofficial theme song. The words -- as any toddler knows -- are, "I love you, 
you love me, we're a happy family, with a great big hug and a kiss from me to 
you. Won't you say you love me too?" 
</P>
<P>
 One of Barney's co-creators heard the tune in a Gymboree class her child 
attended during the mid-'80s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
