<HEADLINE>
<P>
RELIGION NOTES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN DART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 CRUSADE FIGURES: The San Fernando Valley crusade by Luis Palau, which ended 
Sunday, saw 1,442 people make "decisions for Christ," either recommitments of 
faith or first-time professions, during five rallies that drew 45,100 people to 
the Birmingham High School football field in Van Nuys. 
</P>
<P>
 Crusade officials also said that $403,000 in donations was raised to meet the 
budget established by the local organizing committee of business leaders and 
pastors. 
</P>
<P>
 The crowd totals and number of decisions slightly exceeded those at Palau's 
previous major U.S. crusade, held in 1993 in Fort Worth. But the Valley totals 
were below results in Phoenix and San Antonio the two previous years. 
</P>
<P>
 Nevertheless, crusade leaders said the number of volunteers from Valley-area 
churches exceeded the turnout in the other three cities, although the quantity 
of supporting congregations was higher in Fort Worth, Phoenix and San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
 Counting auxiliary events -- including a Latino rally, two luncheons and a 
children's rally -- the total attendance was 54,025, with 2,175 decisions, 
spokesmen said. 
</P>
<P>
 CATHOLIC AWARD: The National Catholic Register, a weekly newspaper edited in 
Encino, won first place in the general excellence category for national 
Catholic newspapers at the recent Catholic Press Assn. meeting in Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 The Register, whose editor is Joop Koopman, beat out Our Sunday Visitor 
(second place), Catholic New Times, Toronto (third place) and the National 
Catholic Reporter (honorable mention). 
</P>
<P>
 AWARDS LUNCHEON: The Rev. Louis B. Gebhardt, a former senior pastor at First 
Congregational Church of Los Angeles who currently serves a church in Fresno, 
will speak at the Clergy Network awards luncheon Thursday at the Marriott Hotel 
in Woodland Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 Gebhardt is chairman of the executive committee of the National Assn. of 
Congregational Christian Churches. 
</P>
<P>
 The noon luncheon will honor Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block, 
publisher-philanthropist Jane Boeckmann, Mother Rosa Broadous of Pacoima's 
Calvary Baptist Church and the Rev. Karl Kniseley, president of UniHealth 
America Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
 For information, call (800) 707-2224. 
</P>
<P>
 SENIOR JOBS: Unemployed and underemployed San Fernando Valley residents 50 and 
older are being invited to sign up for training programs, counseling services 
and job placement resources at an opportunities fair from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. 
Friday at St. Andrew's Lutheran Church in Van Nuys. 
</P>
<P>
 "One in every five people over age 50 live close to poverty . . . but many 
lack the skills to compete in today's job market," said Sally James, executive 
director of Career Encores. 
</P>
<P>
 The fair at the church, 15520 Sherman Way, is one of three sponsored by a 
grant from Food for All, a nonprofit organization. 
</P>
<P>
 There is no charge, but space is limited, sponsors said. Call Career Encores 
at (818) 842-7507 for reservations and information. 
</P>
<P>
 BROADWAY MUSIC: Songs from "The Sound of Music," "Oliver" and "Showboat" will 
be featured in concert at 7 p.m. Sunday at Northridge United Methodist Church, 
9650 Reseda Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
 Admission is $8 for adults and $4 for children to benefit the church's music 
ministry. 
</P>
<P>
 KLEZMER BAND: The five-member Ellis Island Klezmer Band will perform 4 p.m. 
Sunday at Valley Beth Israel, 13060 Roscoe Blvd., Sun Valley, as a part of the 
Jewish Cultural Series sponsored by three San Fernando Valley synagogues. 
</P>
<P>
 Tickets, available at the door, range from $10 for adults to $3.50 for 
children. 
</P>
<P>
 News and announcements for this column may be sent to Religion Desk, Los 
Angeles Times, 20000 Prairie St., Chatsworth 91311. JOHN DART 
</P>
</TEXT>
