<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; FORUM TO EXAMINE POLICE HARASSMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Alliance Working for Asian Rights and Empowerment, or AWARE, will hold a 
forum today on the rights of citizens who are detained or questioned by police. 
</P>
<P>
 People who say they are victims of police harassment, attorneys and 
representatives of the American Civil Liberties Union will be featured speakers 
at the "Copwatch Forum" at the Vietnamese Community of Southern California, 
15361 Brookhurst St. in Westminster. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to educate and inform our youth and parents of our community about 
police harassment -- what it is, and what to do about it," said JoAnn Kanshige, 
co-founder of AWARE. 
</P>
<P>
 The speakers will present a discussion titled: "Guilty by Appearance: Gang 
Hysteria, Mug Files and Youth Rights." 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, Kanshige will share her family's experiences with alleged police 
abuse and her attempts to stop the Fountain Valley Police Department from 
photographing youths for gang mug files. 
</P>
<P>
 Parent Kim Ha is scheduled to describe the book she is writing, which details 
her family's encounters with what she says is police harassment. 
</P>
<P>
 Quyen Pham, a 16-year-old Tustin High School honors student, will describe how 
she and two friends were photographed by police while they waited for a ride 
home in front of a Garden Grove mini-mall restaurant last year. The photos, 
taken in July, are still stored in police files. 
</P>
<P>
 As a result, the ACLU recently filed a class-action federal lawsuit against 
the Garden Grove Police Department, challenging its strategy of photographing 
youths who fit a certain gang profile. 
</P>
<P>
 "We believe that good policing does not require creating mug files of innocent 
people," said Daniel C. Tsang, co-founder of AWARE. 
</P>
<P>
 "Culturally, the Asian community does not speak out against such things as 
police harassment," Kanshige said. "By nature, our people do not complain or 
report abuse, so by having some speak out, we hope to encourage others to do 
the same." 
</P>
<P>
 The forum will be held between 1 p.m. and 3 p.m. MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061194-0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 050475 </DOCID>
