<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; FAIRGROUNDS BUFFALO GETS INDIAN NAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The bison born at the county fairgrounds finally has a name: Tatonka. 
</P>
<P>
 The name was selected from more than 1,000 suggestions made as part of a 
christening contest run by the fairgrounds.Tatonka was born May 11 to Becky, a 
bison refugee from the Buffalo Ranch in Irvine, which closed earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "Buffy" was the name suggested most, perhaps because for the first 20 days of 
the animal's life he was thought by livestock caretakers to be female. No one 
could get close enough to be sure because Becky growled in warning, explained 
fair spokeswoman Georgia Cluver. 
</P>
<P>
 Finally, nature called attention to the animal's gender. "We saw the way it 
relieved itself, and it relieved itself like a male," Cluver said. 
</P>
<P>
 Suggestions for the animal's name poured in from around the Southland and as 
far away as Japan, Cluver said. The panel of four judges plugged their ears to 
the choruses of "Buffy" and picked "Tatonka." It's a Native American word for 
bison that was used in the film "Dances With Wolves," Cluver said Thursday when 
the name was announced. 
</P>
<P>
 Becky and Tatonka live on Centennial Farm, a small working farm at the 
fairgrounds.WILLSON CUMMER 
</P>
</TEXT>
